AKURE – The Bishop, Diocese of Ondo Anglican Communion, Dr Stephen Adenira Oni, has called on the Federal Government and university lecturers, under the aegis of Academic Staff Union of Universities (ASUU), to earnestly find a lasting solution to the incessant crisis between them in the interest of students. He made the call while addressing newsmen at the 70th anniversary of the church in Ondo, in Ondo West Local Government Area of Ondo State. The cleric who decried incessant industrial actions on the nation’s campuses implored the Federal Government to honour the agreement they both reached to face the save the quality and standard of education in the country. Brazil’s Hot Stock Market Gets Boost From MSCI Booting Russia￼ FIBA World Cup: Nigeria’s D’Tigress To Face France In Group B He observed that the academic calendar and the lives of students were undermined by the recurring crises between varsity lecturers and the Federal Government, thereby calling for an end to the crisis. Commending President Muhammadu Buhari for signing the electoral bill into law recently, Bishop Oni urged the Independent National Electoral Commission (INEC) and politicians to ensure strict compliance with dictates of the new electoral act. He said: “We must thank President Muhammadu Buhari for the newly signed Electoral Act 2022. This law must not be manipulated to give an undue advantage to anybody.” The Anglican bishop appreciated the efforts of the heroes both home and in the diaspora who made contributed to the growth of the church. He expressed joy in the church that was planted like a mustard seed planted as a Diocese on February 24, 1952, and had become a veritable apex of evangelism, education, and achievements in all aspects on human endeavours. POLL Bishop Oni disclosed that the Diocese has a world-class multi-million naira  Eye Care Centre where several Nigerians were given free eye treatment, besides 70 flats priests’ residence in the diocese.